        <div>
          <h3>What's the difference between hot mix asphalt (HMA) and warm mix asphalt (WMA)?</h3>
    
        </div>
        <div>
          <p>Hot mix asphalt (HMA) and warm mix asphalt (WMA) differ primarily in their production and application temperatures:</p>
          
          <h4>Hot Mix Asphalt (HMA):</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>Produced at temperatures between 300-350°F (149-177°C)</li>
            <li>Traditional and most common type of asphalt pavement</li>
            <li>Provides excellent durability and performance</li>
            <li>Requires higher energy consumption to maintain temperature during transport</li>
            <li>Must be placed and compacted while hot</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h4>Warm Mix Asphalt (WMA):</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>Produced at reduced temperatures of 250-275°F (121-135°C)</li>
            <li>Uses additives or processes to achieve proper workability at lower temperatures</li>
            <li>Environmental benefits include reduced fuel consumption and emissions</li>
            <li>Can be transported longer distances without excessive cooling</li>
            <li>Extended paving season in cooler weather</li>
            <li>Comparable performance to HMA when properly installed</li>
          </ul>
          
          <p>Both types have similar densities, so this calculator can be used for either HMA or WMA with the appropriate density value.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
